.THE TRANSMISSION WAS CALCULATED FROM THE COUNT LOSS
CORRECTED DATA MINUS THE BACKGROUND. THE BACKGROUND
WAS ASSUMED TO CONSIST OF THREE COMPONENTS:
1. MACHINE INDEPENDENT EVENTS DUE TO COSMIC RAYS AND
LOCAL ACTIVITY
2. TIME INDEPENDENT EVENTS FROM INDUCED LONG LIVED
ACTIVITY FROM NEUTRONS AND GAMMAS RELATED TO
MACHINE OUTPUT
3. TIME DEPENDENT EVENTS FROM NEUTRONS AND GAMMAS
DIRECTLY EMITTED FROM THE FAST NEUTRON TARGET.
BACKGROUND TIME DEPENDENCE WAS MEASURED USING RES-
ONANCE FILTERS OF AR, AL AND LI2CO4. A MODIFIED
VERSION OF THE 'BLACK RESONANCE' TECHNIQUE WAS USED TO
DETERMINE THE SHAPE AND MAGNITUDE OF THE BACKGROUND
USING LEAST SQUARES FITTING TECHNIQUES.

THE LEAST SQUARES SHAPE FITTING PROGRAM REFIT
WAS USED TO DETERMINE THE RESONANCE PARAMATERS FROM
THE COMBINED TRANSMISSION DATA OF HARWELL (EXFOR WORK
22184005 AND 22184006) AND ORNL (LARSON ET AL.,
ORNL/TM-5614, 1976) OVER THE NEUTRON ENERGY RANGE 1 -
480 KEV. RADIATION WIDTHS COULD NOT BE DETERMINED FROM
THE PRESENT DATA AND REMAINED FIXED AT THE VALUES IN
BNL325. REFIT DOES NOT AT PRESENT INCLUDE THE CALCULA-
TION OF INELASTIC SCATTERING IN THE CROSS SECTION
ROUTINE, THUS THE DATA ABOVE 480 KEV COULD NOT BE
FULLY ANALYSED. ABOVE THIS INELASTIC THRESHOLD IT WAS
ASSUMED THERE WERE NO INTERFERENCE TERMS IN THE
INELASTIC CROSS SECTION AND THAT THERE WAS NO CORREL-
ATION BETWEEN THE ELASTIC AND INELASTIC WIDTHS. THE
QUOTED RESONANCE PARAMETERS REPRODUCE THE TOTAL CROSS
SECTION FROM 480 - 550 KEV; ABOVE THIS THE PARAMETERS
DO NOT REPRODUCE THE OBSERVED CROSS SECTION.
STATISTICAL ERRORS ONLY. THERE ARE ADDITIONAL
ERRORS OF +-0.004% DUE TO THE UNCERTAINTY IN FLIGHT
PATH LENGTH, AND AN ESTIMATED +-0.67% DUE TO THE
UNCERTAINTY IN SAMPLE THICKNESS. THIS WILL ONLY
AFFECT THE LARGER NEUTRON WIDTHS WITH FITTED ERRORS
OF LESS THAN 1%.
.DATA TAKEN FROM TABLE I OF MAIN REF.
